<concept id="c_krakow">
    <title>Krakow</title>
    <shortdesc>Main information and short history</shortdesc>
    <conbody>
        <p><b>Kraków</b><sup><xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-6"
                    format="html" scope="external">[a]</xref></sup> (Polish: <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/Polish" format="html" scope="external"
                >[ˈkrakuf]</xref>, also known in English as <b>Cracow</b>, is the second-largest and
            one of the oldest cities in <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poland"
                format="html" scope="external">Poland</xref>. Situated on the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vistula" format="html" scope="external">Vistula
                River</xref> in <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lesser_Poland_Voivodeship"
                format="html" scope="external">Lesser Poland Voivodeship</xref>, the city dates back
            to the seventh century.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-History-7"
                    format="html" scope="external">[6]</xref></sup> Kraków was the official capital
            of Poland until 1596<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-8" format="html"
                    scope="external">[7]</xref></sup> and has traditionally been one of the leading
            centres of Polish academic, economic, cultural and artistic life. Cited as one of
            Europe's most beautiful cities,<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-9" format="html"
                    scope="external">[8]</xref></sup> its <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w_Old_Town" format="html"
                scope="external">Old Town</xref> with <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wawel_Castle" format="html" scope="external"
                >Wawel Royal Castle</xref> was declared the first <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNESCO" format="html" scope="external"
                >UNESCO</xref>
            <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Heritage_Site" format="html"
                scope="external">World Heritage Site</xref> in the world.</p>
        <p>The city has grown from a <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stone_Age"
                format="html" scope="external">Stone Age</xref> settlement to Poland's
            second-most-important city. It began as a hamlet on <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wawel_Castle" format="html" scope="external"
                >Wawel Hill</xref> and was reported as a busy trading centre of Central Europe in
                    965.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-History-7"
                    format="html" scope="external">[6]</xref></sup> With the establishment of new
            universities and cultural venues at the emergence of the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Polish_Republic" format="html"
                scope="external">Second Polish Republic</xref> in 1918 and throughout the 20th
            century, Kraków reaffirmed its role as a major national academic and artistic centre.
            The city has a population of about 780,000, with approximately 8 million additional
            people living within a 100 km (62 mi) radius of its <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Market_Square,_Krak%C3%B3w" format="html"
                scope="external">main square</xref>.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-welcome-10"
                    format="html" scope="external">[9]</xref></sup></p>
        <p>After the <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invasion_of_Poland" format="html"
                scope="external">invasion of Poland</xref> by Nazi Germany at the start of <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_II" format="html" scope="external"
                >World War II</xref>, the newly defined <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distrikt_Krakau" format="html" scope="external"
                >Distrikt Krakau</xref> (Kraków District) became the capital of Germany's <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Government" format="html"
                scope="external">General Government</xref>. The Jewish population of the city was
            forced into a walled zone known as the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w_Ghetto" format="html"
                scope="external">Kraków Ghetto</xref>, from where they were sent to Nazi <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extermination_camp" format="html"
                scope="external">extermination camps</xref> such as the nearby <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auschwitz_concentration_camp" format="html"
                scope="external">Auschwitz</xref>, and <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazi_concentration_camps" format="html"
                scope="external">Nazi concentration camps</xref> like <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w-P%C5%82asz%C3%B3w_concentration_camp"
                format="html" scope="external">Płaszów</xref>.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-ARC-11" format="html"
                    scope="external">[10]</xref></sup> However, the city was spared from destruction
            and major bombing.</p>
        <p>In 1978, Karol Wojtyła, <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archbishop_of_Krak%C3%B3w" format="html"
                scope="external">archbishop of Kraków</xref>, was elevated to the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Papacy" format="html" scope="external"
                >papacy</xref> as <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pope_John_Paul_II"
                format="html" scope="external">Pope John Paul II</xref>—the first non-Italian pope
            in 455 years.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-Clark-12"
                    format="html" scope="external">[11]</xref></sup> Also that year, <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNESCO" format="html" scope="external"
                >UNESCO</xref> approved <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w_Old_Town" format="html"
                scope="external">Kraków's entire Old Town and historic centre</xref> as its first
                <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Heritage_Site" format="html"
                scope="external">World Heritage Site</xref> alongside <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quito" format="html" scope="external"
                >Quito</xref>.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-Centre-13"
                    format="html" scope="external">[12]</xref></sup><sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-unesco-02com-14"
                    format="html" scope="external">[13]</xref></sup> Kraków is classified as a <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_city" format="html" scope="external"
                >global city</xref> with the ranking of "high sufficiency" by the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Globalization_and_World_Cities_Research_Network"
                format="html" scope="external">Globalization and World Cities Research
                Network</xref>.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-15" format="html"
                    scope="external">[14]</xref></sup> Its extensive cultural heritage across the
            epochs of <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gothic_architecture" format="html"
                scope="external">Gothic</xref>, <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renaissance_architecture" format="html"
                scope="external">Renaissance</xref> and <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baroque_architecture" format="html"
                scope="external">Baroque architecture</xref> includes <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wawel_Cathedral" format="html" scope="external"
                >Wawel Cathedral</xref> and <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wawel_castle"
                format="html" scope="external">Wawel Royal Castle</xref> on the banks of the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vistula" format="html" scope="external"
                >Vistula</xref>, <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Mary%27s_Basilica,_Krak%C3%B3w"
                format="html" scope="external">St. Mary's Basilica</xref>, <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saints_Peter_and_Paul_Church,_Krak%C3%B3w"
                format="html" scope="external">Saints Peter and Paul Church</xref> and the largest
                <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medieval" format="html" scope="external"
                >medieval</xref> market square in Europe, <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Square,_Krak%C3%B3w" format="html"
                scope="external">Rynek Główny</xref>.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-16" format="html"
                    scope="external">[15]</xref></sup> Kraków is home to <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jagiellonian_University" format="html"
                scope="external">Jagiellonian University</xref>, one of the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_oldest_universities_in_continuous_operation"
                format="html" scope="external">oldest universities in the world</xref> and
            traditionally Poland's most reputable institution of higher learning.</p>
        <p>In 2000, Kraków was named <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Capital_of_Culture" format="html"
                scope="external">European Capital of Culture</xref>. In 2013, Kraków was officially
            approved as a <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNESCO_City_of_Literature"
                format="html" scope="external">UNESCO City of Literature</xref>.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-17" format="html"
                    scope="external">[16]</xref></sup> The city hosted <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Youth_Day" format="html" scope="external"
                >World Youth Day</xref> in July 2016.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-18" format="html"
                    scope="external">[17]</xref></sup></p>
